In article <2ohp1h$7ei@agate.berkeley.edu>,
Nicholas C. Weaver <nweaver@boojum.CS.Berkeley.EDU> wrote:
>
>	Is there a good one way hash function which takes data and a salt S
>such that H( H(D, S1), S2) = H( H(D, S2), S1)????  
>
>	My 170 professor has challanged me to come up with a solution to the
>Dining Cryptographers problem (with a large number of cryptographers) where
>two cryptographers who try to get together can't find out much extra
>information, and I THINK I might have a chance if I can find a one way hash
>with the property above.

The canonical one is Diffie-Hellman.  Given a large prime p
and a generator of the group Z^*_p g, you form

(g^s1)^s2 == (g^s2)^s1 == g^(s1*s2) (mod p).
But to go from g^s (mod p) to s requires solving the discrete log
problem, which is hard if p > 512 bits or so.
-- 
	-Colin
